<H3> <TI>   Journalists Association Meets in Beijing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Journalists Association Meets in Beijing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2704161894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1558 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2704161894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 27 (XINHUA) -- The second plenary 
session of the Fourth Council of the Chinese Journalists 
Association (CJA) opened today in Beijing. 
  CJA Vice-Chairman Li Yan made a report at the meeting on the 
work of the association. More than 200 members of the council 
in mass media across the country took part in the meeting. 
  Li hailed the great contributions the association has made 
over the past three years in developing China's journalism. 
  Talking about the association's future task, Li said the 
role 
of "bridges" and ties of the association as a non-governmental 
organization should be brought into full play. 
  He said the association must better serve all journalists, 
uniting and promoting the press circles to make greater 
contributions toward new success in China's reform, opening and 
modernization drive. 
  The vice-chairman added that the CJA should make positive 
efforts to push forward the exchanges and cooperation between 
Chinese journalists and overseas journalists. 
  He noted that as an authoritative non-governmental 
organization the CJA should adapt itself to meet the demands of 
the time and the journalists, broaden mass viewpoints and play a 
better role as a bridge and tie in the new situation. 
  He said that China has more than 500,000 people who are 
engaged in journalism. 
  Xu Weicheng, deputy director of the Propaganda Department of 
the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee, also spoke at the 
meeting. 
  Xu said that it is necessary to adhere to the correct 
orientation of the ideological and media work, serving the 
economic construction, reform and opening, and social and 
political stability. 

</TEXT>

