<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-082 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Measures To Control Foreign Investments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Measures To Control Foreign Investments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604163894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1517 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Wuhan, April 26 (XINHUA) -- In an effort to further 
tighten the management of foreign investment assets, China will 
enact new methods of their appraisal and management from May 1, 
according to a national conference held recently in Wuhan, 
capital of central China's Hubei Province. 
  The methods were jointly stipulated by the State 
Administration for the Inspection of Import and Export 
Commodities and the Ministry of Finance. 
  In recent years, foreign investment in China has risen 
rapidly. By the end of 1993, China had approved 170,000 
foreign-funded enterprises, involving 210 billion U.S. dollars 
in contracted foreign funds, 60 billion U.S. dollars of which 
were finally put to use. Eighty percent of the investment was 
in the form of machines and equipment and margins existed 
between their value and evaluation. 
  In 1993, the State Administration for the Inspection of 
Import and Export Commodities re-evaluated 2,121 cases of 
foreign investment assets, claimed by owners to be worth more 
than 965 million U.S. dollars, and found that they were worth 
slightly over 800 million U.S. dollars. 
  The appraisals to be adopted will cover variety, quality, 
quantity, value and losses. Appraisals of variety, quality and 
quantity will cover the assets' names, types, quality, quantity, 
size, trademark, rate of obsolescence, date of production, 
nation of origin and manufacturer. Value appraisal will cover 
the contemporary evaluation of foreign investment assets and 
loss appraisal will cover the reasons and degrees of losses 
caused by natural disasters and accidents, cost of clearing up 
losses and remaining value of the assets. 
  The State Administration for the Inspection of Import and 
Export Commodities will take charge of the nationwide appraisal 
of foreign investment assets and its local bureaus will take 
care of the local appraisal work. 
  To deal with the examination of foreign investment assets, 
an 
accounting office must hold a value appraisal certificate of the 
State Administration for the Inspection of Import and Export 
Commodities or other relevant organizations, the "methods" said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

