<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cooperation With Multi-Nationals To Increase </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cooperation With Multi-Nationals To Increase </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604150094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1433 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604150094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 26 (XINHUA) -- Beijing's 
manufacturing industries will step up cooperation with 
multi-national companies over the next seven years, a municipal 
government official said today. 
  Addressing a news conference today, Gao Zuozhi, director of 
the Municipal Economic Commission, invited multi-national 
companies to invest in such priority industries as automobiles, 
electronics, meters, new chemicals, new building materials, 
pharmaceuticals, clothing, food processing, computers, 
program-controlled switchboards, and integrated circuits. 
  Specifically, he said, Beijing seeks cooperation with 
multi-national companies and other overseas firms in 
manufacturing goods with a low consumption of energy, raw 
materials or water, but with a high added value. 
  Beijing also wishes to cooperate with overseas investors in 
moving factories in downtown areas to suburbs and undertaking 
real estate development projects and building service-oriented 
companies there, he added. 
  Gao also revealed that Beijing has set up a number of major 
joint ventures with multi-national companies, including the NEC 
Company of Japan, the Chrysler Company of the United States, the 
Philips Corporation of the Netherlands and ABB Company of 
Switzerland. 
  By the end of 1993 manufacturers in Beijing had established 
40 major joint ventures with overseas firms, each involving at 
least 10 million U.S. dollars in foreign investment, he said. 
  These ventures involve 2.08 billion U.S. dollars in total 
foreign investment, he added. 

</TEXT>

