<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beijing Drafting First Negotiable Instruments Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beijing Drafting First Negotiable Instruments Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604142994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1416 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 26 (XINHUA) -- China is speeding up 
drafting of its first law on negotiable instruments, in a bid to 
ensure their safe and smooth circulation. 
  An official from the Bureau of Legislative Affairs under the 
State Council said here today that the legislation on negotiable 
instruments in China has become increasingly imperative as the 
market economy is developing rapidly. 
  Speaking at a seminar on negotiable instruments held by the 
Chinese Chamber of International Commerce (CCIC) and the Chamber 
of International Commerce, the official said that the National 
People's Congress and the State Council have attached great 
importance to the work on such a law. 
  The legislative branch has already put the draft and viewing 
of the law on its top agenda. 
  China began its work on drafting the law in 1990 and the 
initial draft has taken shape. 
  The official said that the drafting group did research not 
only on the use and circulation of domestic negotiable 
instruments but made studies on the relevant laws abroad. 
  Xu Dayou, vice president of CCIC, said that the seminar was 
aimed at better understanding foreign laws on negotiable 
instruments and international experiences in the area by Chinese 
lawyers, financiers and industrialists, in order to standardize 
Chinese actions of negotiable instruments in international trade 
and investment fields and ensure the normal use and circulation 
of negotiable instruments. 
  During the two-day meeting, experts on checks and bills from 
the Chamber of International Commerce and Britain will exchange 
views with Chinese legislators and financiers on international 
norms on rules, structures, sorts and actions of negotiable 
instruments as well as the current situation of the use of 
negotiable instruments in China. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4058 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi082_n_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-082 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Draft Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Draft Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2704080394 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 27 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK2704080394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By staff reporter Ma Chenguang: "Negotiable Notes To Be </F>
Regulated With New Law"] 
  [Text] China is introducing a law on bills of exchange to 
better regulate their proper use and circulation, an official 
from the State Council said yesterday. 
  The draft of the Law on Negotiable Instruments has been 
completed and will be submitted to the State Council for 
deliberation soon, said Li Shishi from the council's Legislative 
Affairs Bureau. 
  As indicated in the draft, negotiable instruments will 
include bills of exchange, promissory notes, bearer shares, 
bonds and negotiable certificates of deposits, Li said at an 
international seminar in Beijing. 
  The law is intended to ensure the proper handling of 
transactions involving payments, exchanges, credit, and 
financing and dissolving debts. 
  The introduction of a socialist market economy in China has 
led to the increasing use of various negotiable instruments for 
finance, investment and international trade. The growing role 
these documents play calls for a timely law to regulate their 
use . 
  The lack of such a law has resulted in disputes and crimes, 
such as circulation of bad checques and fake bills, he said. 
According to the draft law, these crimes will be severely 
punished. 
  The law will stipulate the pattern of negotiable instruments 
and the information that they must include. It also will 
establish details about the transfer of holders' rights and cash 
deposits and the effectiveness period for the documents. 
  Research for the draft began in 1990 and was mainly compiled 
by experts from the People's Bank of China, he said. After 
deliberation at the State Council, the law will be submitted to 
China's legislature for approval. 
  Li spoke at a two-day seminar on negotiable instruments, 
which was organized by the China Chamber of International 
Commerce and the International Chamber of Commerce. 
  The organizers said they wished to draw useful experiences 
from other countries through the seminar to provide perspective 
for China's compilation of its law. 
  Analysts at the seminar said the draft law is expected to be 
passed this year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4059 </DOCNO>
