<H3> <TI>   Mayor Invites Overseas Banks To Open Branches in Beijing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mayor Invites Overseas Banks To Open Branches in Beijing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2704080194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0717 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2704080194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 27 (XINHUA)--Beijing Mayor Li Qiyan 
today invited banks from Japan and other countries to open 
subsidiaries in China's capital. 
  In a meeting with Kuniji Miyazaki, chairman of the Daiichi 
Kangyo Bank of Japan, Li said that China was now shifting to a 
market economy, so it needed to have a variety of means to raise 
money. 
  He said that through mutual exchanges, overseas business 
people would certainly enhance their confidence in investing in 
China. 
  "I am optimistic that Japanese banks will open branches in 
Beijing," he told Miyazaki and his party. 
  Kuniji Miyazaki, who visited Beijing two years ago, said 
that 
during his current visit he wishes to discuss cooperation with 
his Chinese colleagues in banking reform. 
  He said that his bank plans to hold financial symposiums in 
Shanghai and in Dalian, Liaoning Province. 
  "I am sure that China will score even greater achievements 
in 
its economic construction," he said. 
  The Daiichi Kangyo Bank, the largest commercial bank in 
Japan, had raised a total of 1.8 billion U.S. dollars for China 
by the end of 1993. 
  It currently has a branch in Shanghai and offices in 
Beijing, 
Dalian, Xiamen and Guangzhou. 

</TEXT>

