<H3> <TI>   Beijing Sets Up `Shopping Center' for Writers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beijing Sets Up `Shopping Center' for Writers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2704120994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0759 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2704120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 27 (XINHUA)--Beijing Association of 
Writers recently set up a computerised "shopping center" where 
publishers can see what manuscripts different writers currently 
have on offer for publication. 
  The center collects a brief synopsis of each manuscript and 
also summarizes writers' future literary plans. 
  All this computerised information can be accessed by 
publishers looking for works to produce. 
  Already more than 300 writers, including some noted ones 
such 
as Zhang Jie, Lin Jinlan, Liu Shaotang, Lei Jia and Luo Binji, 
have presented their authorship plans to the center. 
  The 1,000 manuscripts it has received include novels, 
historical fiction, martial-arts fiction, biography, popular 
stories, children's stories, scientific and technological works, 
translations of foreign literature and academic works, current 
affairs, and poetry. 
  Last week the center held a talk for more than 30 publishers 
who showed interest in a dozen subjects stored at the center. 
  Young writer Cui Jingsheng has signed a contract with Hebei 
People's Publishing house to print his novel, "Seven Bachelors", 
and received an advance of 1,000 yuan. 

</TEXT>

