<F P=100> PRC MEDIA ON TAIWAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Courts To Handle Qiandao Lake Incident `As Scheduled' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Courts To Handle Qiandao Lake Incident `As Scheduled' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2704145594 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1312 GMT 
27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2704145594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hangzhou, April 27 (CNS) -- The Qiandao Lake 
incident in which a group of Taiwan tourists died will be dealt 
with by the Hangzhou Intermediate People's Court and the 
Zhejiang Higher People's Court, the Director of the Zhejiang 
branch of the Taiwan Affairs Office Mr. Ma Guangwu said in an 
interview with the Taiwan news media. He stressed that the case 
would go to court as scheduled no matter when the 
representatives of the Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF) of 
Taiwan came. The three suspects will stand trial at a time the 
official has not yet disclosed, simply noting that the start of 
the trial would not be deferred for too long a period. 
  Mr. Ma said that as the case involved Taiwan compatriots as 
well as Mainland persons, the trial would in no way be conducted 
to appease the anger shown by the Taiwan side. He added that 
whether the SEF representatives came was not a factor and the 
case would go ahead as scheduled. 
  He revealed that the Zhejiang authorities had learned a 
lesson from the incident and they called departments of travel, 
transport and public security to a meeting on improvement of 
travel safety. A conference held in the province on tourist 
safety will make public its results following the arrival of the 
SEF personnel. 
  In another development, Chairman of the "Mainland Affairs 
Council" of the "Executive Yuan" of Taiwan Mr. Huang Kum-huei 
and the Secretary General of SEF Mr. Chiao Jen-ho, in response 
to a letter by the Mainland Association for Relations Across the 
Taiwan Strait (ARATS) inviting SEF to send personnel to Hangzhou 
to look into the case, said that the Taiwan side accepted in 
principle the invitation. The council has asked SEF to reply to 
the proposal by ARATS and held consultations today for a final 
decision on the invitation. 
  The "Minister of Economic Affairs" of Taiwan Mr. Chiang 
Pin-kung said yesterday that following the announcement 
regarding dealing with the case by the Mainland side, the true 
picture of the incident was tending to become clearer. He 
stressed that cross-strait economic exchange and trade should 
return to normal step by step. 

</TEXT>

