<DATE1>  26 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Ties With PRC `Anticipated To Resume' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economic Ties With PRC `Anticipated To Resume' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604135194 Taipei CNA in English 1322 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604135194 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Benjamin Yeh] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 26 (CNA) -- Economic Affairs Minister 
P.K. Chiang said on Tuesday [26 April] that cross-strait 
economic and trade ties put on hold in the wake of the Qiandao 
Lake disaster are anticipated to resume as before. 
  Chiang called the incident an isolated happenstance, and 
said 
that now that Beijing has concluded its inquiry into the case, 
the barrier that has blocked cross-strait ties for more than 
three weeks should be partly removed. 
  Beijing announced last week that three suspects had been 
seized for robbing and killing 24 Taiwan tourists, two mainland 
guides and six crewmen aboard a cruise boat touring the lake, 
which is in the eastern province of Zhejiang. 
  Beijing's handling of the incident included a cover-up 
attempt and the restriction of the victims' relatives' movement, 
and prompted the government to put a brake on bilateral ties. 
  The Ministry of Economic Affairs earlier in the month 
suspended screening applications for mainland-bound investments 
and said it would not continue to raise the quotas for mainland 
raw materials and semi-finished products allowed into Taiwan. 
  Chiang said the purpose behind the ministry's decision was 
to 
call attention to the high risks Taiwan investors face on the 
mainland. Now that this has been accomplished, he said, 
mainland investment and expanded import of mainland materials 
can continue, as long as the Mainland Affairs Council approves. 
  Chiang's remarks are seen by many here as a gesture of eased 
tensions between Taipei and Beijing. Just after the disaster, 
President Li Teng-hui was indignant, saying the mainland was 
ruled by a group of "bandits" who should be overthrown by the 
people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4098 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi082_v_94004" </HT>


