<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-082 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Germany Denies Plan To Sell Submarines to Taipei </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Germany Denies Plan To Sell Submarines to Taipei </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2704135994 Taipei CNA in English 1333 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2704135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn, April 27 (CNA) -- The German Foreign Affairs 
Ministry said Wednesday [27 April] that the German Government 
has no plans to sell 10 submarines to Taiwan, as had been 
reported in Germany. 
  The economic daily HANDELSBLATT reported Wednesday that the 
Grman firms HDW, Vulkan, Thyssen Nordseewerke, and Blohm Und 
Voss contacted US arms contractors last year about assembling 
submarine parts made in Germany and then shipping the finished 
submarines to Taiwan. The German Government said it never gave 
permission to the companies to enter into such a deal, and that 
it was adhering to a ban on sales of weaponry to countries it 
considers to be in "high tension" areas. 
  Delivery of the submarines to Taiwan, the paper said, would 
secure for Germany another contract for high speed ice rains [as 
received] worth 30 million marks (US$17.6 billion). 
  Taiwan's efforts to purchase submarines and other weaponry 
from Germany have been stalled as Bonn does not want to damage 
its ties with Beijing. Communist China has repeatedly insisted 
that no country should sell weapons to Taiwan because it is 
under Beijing sovereignty. 
  In Taipei, German Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt told 
the 
press on Tuesday that his government is reviewing the present 
list of high tension areas, but did not say whether the list 
would be amended to exclude Taiwan. 
  Rexrodt, the second highest ranking official from Germany to 
visit Taiwan, is visiting Taiwan to lobby on behalf of German 
firms bidding for construction contracts related to the building 
of the proposed high speed railway. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

