<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Discusses U.S. Trade Relations, Human Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Discusses U.S. Trade Relations, Human Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2704153394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1516 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2704153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Macao, April 27 (XINHUA) -- China is willing to 
exchange views and make research on human rights with other 
countries, however, any attempt to use human rights as a tool to 
put pressure on others would be fruitless. 
  Wu Yi, minister of the Chinese Foreign Trade and Economic 
Cooperation, made these remarks at a news conference held here 
this evening. 
  She said the question of the most favored nation (MFN) 
trading status was a core item in the trade agreement signed 
between the governments of China and the United States when the 
two countries established diplomatic relations in 1979, adding 
it is also the fundamental basis for the trade development 
between the two sides. 
  Wu said MFN is purely a question of trading, saying that 
China will absolutely not accept any attempt to connect MFN with 
matters which have nothing to do with trade, especially the 
human rights. 
  She said that at present, China has set up trade relations 
with 228 countries and regions worldwide and is not afraid of 
confrontations that would take place over MFN. 
  She expressed the hope that the United States would properly 
deal with the MFN issue, saying confrontation will be harmful to 
both China and the U.S. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

