<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Taipei Not To Attend CITES Regional Meeting in Beijing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Taipei Not To Attend CITES Regional Meeting in Beijing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2804085894 Taipei CNA in English 0828 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804085894 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Danielle Yang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, April 28 (CNA) -- Taiwan will not attend 
the convention on International Trade in Endangered Species 
(CITES) Animals Committee meeting in Beijing, according to the 
Council of Agriculture (COA). 
  A COA official confirmed Thursday [28 April] that Beijing 
has 
rejected Taiwan's application to attend the CITES Asian regional 
meeting on the grounds that Taiwan is not a CITES member. 
  However, local conservation groups, including the Beautiful 
Taiwan Foundation and Green Consumer Foundation said they will 
contact Animal Committee Chairman Robert Jenkins to lobby for 
Taiwan's attendance. 
  A three-member civilian delegation was originally set to 
represent the COA at the meeting which Beijing said is an 
official meeting of CITES member countries. Taiwan is not a 
CITES member. 
  The delegation included Professor Li Ling-ling of National 
Taiwan University's Zoology Department, Professor Wang Ing of 
National Normal University's Biology Department, and Professor 
Chang Hsien- che of the China Medical College. 
  The biennial CITES Animals Committee meeting is a warm-up 
for 
the 1994 CITES meeting, which is scheduled to open in Florida 
this November. 
  Both the COA and local conservation groups hope to attend 
the 
committee meeting since it will discuss the future direction of 
international wildlife management. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

