<H3> <TI>   Further on Foreign Ministry's Weekly Briefing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Foreign Ministry's Weekly Briefing </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Comments on South Africa, Japan </H4>

<F P=102> HK2804134394 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1230 GMT 
28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2804134394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 28 (CNS) -- Spokesman of China's 
Ministry of Foreign affairs, Mr. Wu Jianmin, replying to a 
question raised by a reporter at a news briefing held here today 
asking for his comments on and China's hopes regarding the 
forming of the Japanese cabinet by the new Prime Minister, Mr. 
Tsutomu Hata, said that the Chinese Premier Mr. Li Peng had sent 
a congratulatory message to Mr. Hata on his election as prime 
minister of Japan and he added that Mr. Hata was a well-known 
statesman to the Chinese people. China appreciated his zeal and 
farsightedness as well as his contribution to the strengthening 
of Sino-Japanese friendly cooperation. All Japanese political 
parties both in power or not had the same stance on the 
development of mutual cooperation in various fields between the 
two countries. China believed that after the establishment of 
the new Japanese government, the two countries would continue 
their close coordination and cooperation and make joint efforts 
to promote the development of Sino-Japanese ties in a long-term 
and steady way. 
  In answering a question on who China will send to take part 
in the inauguration ceremony of the new president of South 
Africa, Mr. Wu said that the inauguration of the new presient of 
South Africa signaled the end of racist rule and the start of 
national equality in the country. China had all along firmly 
supported the just struggle of the people of South Africa. 
China was glad to see the historical victory won by them and 
would like to express its congratulations to the inauguration 
ceremony of the new president of South Africa. 
  In a separate development, the spokesman announced that at 
the invitation of Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li 
Peng, the President of the Republic of Kenya, Mr. Daniel Arap 
Moi, would pay a state visit to China from May 3 to 7 and the 
Malaysian Prime Minister, Dr. Mahathir Mohammed would pay a 
working visit to China from May 11 to 13. 

</TEXT>

