<H3> <TI>   Moscow, Bonn Suggest Foreign Ministers Meeting on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow, Bonn Suggest Foreign Ministers Meeting on Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2904030894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0226 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2904030894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn, April 28 (XINHUA) -- Moscow and Bonn today 
suggested a meeting of foreign ministers from the United States, 
Britain, Russia, France and Germany to push for an end to the 
war in Bosnia. 
  The meeting would also include representatives from the 
three 
warring sides, according to the proposal put forward here by 
visiting Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and his German 
counterpart Klaus Kinkel. 
  Such a meeting would help iron out differences in policy 
among the consulting countries and, if successful, would pave 
the way for a summit on the conflict between the five nations, 
said Kozyrev. 
  Kinkel stressed Russia's participation in peaceful efforts 
to 
end the civil war in the former Yugoslavia. He also demanded 
that Russia exert pressure on the Bosnian serbs. 
  Kozyrev's meeting with Kinkel followed talks earlier this 
week with U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher, as well as 
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe, aimed at finding ways to 
promote an end to the war in Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

