<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former UN Commander Says Common Strategy Needed on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former UN Commander Says Common Strategy Needed on Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2904060294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0532 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2904060294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, April 28 (XINHUA) -- Western Europe, the 
United States and Russia need to map out and implement a "common 
strategy" in resolving the Bosnian crisis, a former U.N. 
commander in Bosnia said today. 
  The crisis is being prolonged because of a lack of unity in 
the world community, Francis Briquemont, former commander of the 
U.N. peacekeeping forces in Bosnia, said in the local media. 
  Earlier this month, NATO issued two ultimatums to the 
Bosnian 
serbs but did not imposed the same pressure on the other two 
warring sides, Muslims and Croats, he explained. 
  General Briquemont, who retired from the post in January, 
stressed that the "game of two against one" can only deepen the 
crisis. 
  Differences on Bosnia among the big powers has led the 
warring sides to have a "wrong vision" and to make "wrong 
judgements", the general added. 
  Along with a common strategy, Briquemont indicated, the 
world 
community must make it clear to the warring parties that "the 
use of arms will not resolve any problems, but will only hurt 
each nationality". 
  Referring to NATO air strikes on Bosnian Serb positions, the 
general said that representatives of the United Nations should 
not give in to "political pressure" by asking for such action. 
  The general further stated that air strikes against the 
Bosnian Serbs will not resolve the crisis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

