<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Representative Addresses UNCTAD Meeting in Geneva </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Representative Addresses UNCTAD Meeting in Geneva </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2704122294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0616 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2704122294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, April 26 (XINHUA) -- The needs of the 
developing countries should be fully considered in the 
implementation of the final agreement of the Uruguay Round 
talks, Chinese delegate Tang Yufeng said here today. 
  He made the remarks at the 40th session of the Trade and 
Development Board of the U.N. Conference on Trade and 
Development (UNCTAD). 
  Tang pointed out that the conclusion of the Uruguay Round 
talks and the creation of a World Trade Organization (WTO) will 
undoubtedly have an impact on the world trade structure and the 
economic development of different countries till the early next 
century. 
  The agreement in a whole, however, hasn't reached an 
expected 
overall balance and in particular hasn't given a full 
consideration to the interests and demands of the developing 
countries, said Tang. 
  For example, tariff cuts on some largely-exported products 
of 
the developing countries didn't achieve the desired objective, 
he said. 
  Besides, reduction of subsidies to agricultural products 
failed to give due consideration to those developing countries 
which are net grain importers, he added. 
  The Chinese delegate stressed that the developing countries 
have played an active role in the GATT negotiations and they 
should be given full and equal chances to participate in the 
establishment of WTO and a future multilateral trade system. 
  Representatives from other countries also called for much 
more attention to the interests of the developing countries 
during the implementation of the agreement, especially in the 
areas of primary products, grain subsidies and intellectual 
properties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

