<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shanghai Center for International Air Travel </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shanghai Center for International Air Travel </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2904022394 Beijing XINHUA in English 0116 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2904022394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, April 29 (XINHUA) -- Shanghai has become a 
center for international airlines with direct flights to 27 
cities in 16 countries and regions in the world. 
  At present, one in every five airplanes leaving Shanghai, 
one 
of the most rapidly developing areas in the world, flies outside 
China. In 1993, the airport handled 11,913 international 
flights, an increase of 42 percent over the same period of the 
previous year, 26 percent higher than the growth rate of 
domestic flights. 
  Both Chinese and foreign air companies have shown great 
interest in the market, which had its first international 
flight, from Dhaka to Shanghai via Guangzhou, on April 29, 1964. 
  Over the past 30 years, Shanghai's international air 
services 
have developed rapidly. 
  At the beginning of air service between China and Japan, 
Shanghai had only four flights every week with less than 400 
passengers. Now it has 30 Tokyo-bound flights every week. Air 
China, China Eastern Airlines, All Nippon Airways, Japan 
Airlines, Northwest Airlines and United Airlines all have 
business in Shanghai. 
  In 1993, Philippine Airlines, Thai Airways and Lufthansa 
Airlines opened international flights to Shanghai, pushing the 
number of air companies in Shanghai up to thirteen. 
  Of the 30 international flights originating in Shanghai, the 
longest ends in Madrid of Spain, via a dozen or so countries. 
The total distance is 14,326 km and the flight lasts 19 hours. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

