<H3> <TI>   NPC's Chen Muhua Departs for New York UN Ceremony </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NPC's Chen Muhua Departs for New York UN Ceremony </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2904094094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0849 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2904094094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 29 (XINHUA) -- Chen Muhua, 
vice-chairman of China's National People's Congress Standing 
Committee (NPC), left here today for New York to attend a 
ceremony for the presentation of 1994 Maurice Pate Award of the 
United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF). 
  Chen is also president of the All-China Women's Federation. 
  The UNICEF has decided to confer the award on the All-China 
Women's Federation in recognition of its role in promoting the 
Chinese urban and rural women's involvement in development, 
helping them learn culture and technology and raising their 
social status and improving the survival, health and development 
of women and children. 
  The award was set up in 1965 in commemoration of Maurice 
Pate, the first executive director of the UNICEF. The All-China 
Women's Federation is the first recipient of the award as a 
non-governmental organization in China. 
  Seeing Chen off at the airport were Huang Qizao, 
vice-president of the federation, Wang Shuming, deputy 
secretary-general of the NPC Standing Committee, and Dr. Robert 
Parker, senior programme officer of the UNICEF. 

</TEXT>

