<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Cites Yeltsin's Comments on Civic Accord Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    XINHUA Cites Yeltsin's Comments on Civic Accord Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2804164894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1506 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804164894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, April 28 (XINHUA) -- President Boris Yeltsin 
today urged Russians to restore accord in Russia and called the 
signing of the civil accord treaty "an event of historical 
importance." 
  Opening the signing ceremony held in the Kremlin, the 
Russian 
president stressed the need to stop the bloody events, to remove 
the shadow of civil war from Russia and to put an end to civil 
confrontation. 
  He noted any party, organization and mass movement can join 
the treaty, proposed by him in late February immediately after 
the State Duma (the lower house of the parliament) declared the 
political amnesty for his main opponents including former 
Vice-President Aleksandr Rutskoy and former parliament Speaker 
Ruslan Khasbulatov. 
  This can be done by all who are ready to assume 
responsibility for civil peace in the country, Yeltsin said. 
"The key idea of this document is non-violence in achieving 
political goals," he added. 
  Present at the signing ceremony were the president, Prime 
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, Duma Speaker Ivan Rybkin, chairman 
of the federation council (the upper house of the parliament) 
Vladimir Shumeyko, leaders of local regions, and heads of 
parliamentary groups, political parties, mass movements, trade 
unions and religious denominations. 
  The president urged participants in the ceremony for 
reconciliation, "Let us help Russia to get rid of civil war 
forever for the sake of preserving the fatherland and calm of 
our children. Let our joint efforts be crowned with success," 
Yeltsin stated. 
  Speaking at the ceremony, Shumeyko expressed the hope that 
"this treaty is not for politicians and public figures but for 
the whole people." 
  Rybkin noted in his speech that all the participants had 
proclaimed "the need to ease social tension, develop normal 
relations between the branches of power and deepen economic 
reforms in the interests of the entire people." 
  At the ceremony, Patriarch Alexiy II of Moscow stressed the 
need to "continue and deepen our (Russians) accord and, finally 
realize that we are responsible for Russia and its future." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

