<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tian Jiyun Views Cooperation With New Zealand </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tian Jiyun Views Cooperation With New Zealand </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204142994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1140 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Auckland, April 22 (XINHUA) -- There are broad 
prospects for the cooperation between China and New Zealand [NZ] 
in the economic and technological fields and trade. 
  This was stated by Tian Jiyun, vice chairman of the Standing 
Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress when 
addressing the New Zealand-China Trade Association here this 
afternoon. 
  He listed the major achievements made by the two countries 
in 
their economic cooperation in recent years and expressed the 
hope that more NZ business people and government officials will 
visit China to deepen mutual understanding. 
  After briefing the New Zealand businessmen on the reforms in 
China, Tian pledged that "China will open wider to the world." 
  He said that "to maintain and expand the influx of foreign 
investment, we should further improve the environment for such 
investment and the laws and regulations applying to it." 
  "We should protect the legitimate rights and interests of 
enterprises with exclusively foreign investment and use the 
government's industrial policies to channel such investment into 
basic industries and infrastructure," he concluded. 

</TEXT>

