<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tian Jiyun-Led Delegation Ends Visit to New Zealand </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tian Jiyun-Led Delegation Ends Visit to New Zealand </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2304104694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0856 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2304104694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Auckland, April 23 (XINHUA) -- The delegation of 
the Chinese National People's Congress (NPC) led by vice 
chairman of its Standing Committee Tian Jiyun left here for 
Apia, Western Samoa, tonight at the end of its six-day visit to 
New Zealand. 
  During his stay in New Zealand, Tian Jiyun met with New 
Zealand Parliament Speaker Peter Tapsell, Prime Minister Jim 
Bolger and other high-ranking government officials. He also had 
extensive contacts with New Zealand business people. 
  The NPC delegation also visited some agricultural, forestry, 
fishery and educational institutes in Christchurch, Wellington, 
Palmerston North, Hamilton and Auckland. 
  Apart from Western Samoa, the NPC delegation will also go to 
Papua New Guinea and Australia to complete its four-nation South 
Pacific tour. 
  Among those seeing the the delegation off at the airport 
were 
Chinese Ambassador to New Zealand Li Jinhua, Consul-General in 
Auckland Chen Qidao and representatives of the Chinese community 
here. 

</TEXT>

