<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Western Samoan Leaders Meet NPC Delegation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Western Samoan Leaders Meet NPC Delegation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604124294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1116 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604124294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Wellington, April 26 (XINHUA) -- Western Samoa Head 
of State Malietoa Tanumafili II and Prime Minister Tofilau Eti 
Alesana met Monday [25 April] respectively the visiting 
delegation of the Chinese National People's Congress (NPC), 
according to a report reaching here today from Apia. 
  In his meeting with Tian Jiyun, Malietoa expressed his 
gratitude to China for its assistance to Western Samoa, while 
Tian, leader of the delegation and vice chairman of the NPC 
Standing Committee, briefed the head of state on the domestic 
situation in China and China's independent peace foreign policy. 
  Prime Minister Tofilau told Tian that Western Samoa enjoys 
good relations with China which are based on mutual respect and 
understanding. 
  He reaffirmed that the Western Somoa Government abides by 
the 
relevant resolution of the United Nations and holds that there 
is only one China in the world, that is the People's Republic of 
China. 
  Taiwan is part of China, he said, adding Western Samoa has 
no 
official relations whatsoever with Taiwan. 
  Tian expressed appreciation of the position declared by 
Tofilau on the Taiwan issue. 
  He said China and Western Samoa have good relations in the 
political, economic, cultural fields, and there are broad 
prospects for their cooperation. 
  He proposed the governments, parliaments and business 
circles 
of China and Western Somoa increase exchange of visits to 
promote mutual understanding and the development of trade and 
economic cooperation between the two countries. 
  On Saturday, Western Samoa Parliament Speaker Afamasaga Fatu 
Vaili also met the NPC delegation. 
  The delegation arrived in Apia on Saturday morning on the 
second leg of its four-nation south Pacific tour, which also 
covers New Zealand, Papua New Guinea and Australia. 

</TEXT>

