<F P=100> Sub-Saharan Africa </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kenyan President Interviewed on Upcoming Visit to China </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kenyan President Interviewed on Upcoming Visit to China </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2804122594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1115 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804122594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Nairobi, April 28 (XINHUA) -- Kenya President Daniel 
arap Moi has said that relations between Kenya and China are 
excellent. 
  In a exclusive interview with XINHUA and China Radio 
International before his third state visit to China scheduled 
for next Tuesday [3 May], President arap Moi said Kenya and 
China are cooperating very well with each other in domains such 
as politics, education, culture, economy and trade. 
  He highly commended the Chinese personnel in various 
projects 
in Kenya for their hard but enthusiastic work. 
  President arap Moi said that Kenya in Africa is far from 
China in Asia, but they are both developing countries, and are 
facing the common tasks that all developing countries are facing. 
  He rapped the press in Western developed countries over 
ignoring to report various development in Third World countries. 
Instead, he said, they attack them on the so-called 
human-rights issue which was a gross distortion of facts. 
  He warned the Western media not to create unrest in 
developing countries by using the stick of human-rights. 
  Referring to the problems the developing countries are 
facing, President arap Moi said that the main issues in the 
present world are peace and development, adding that where there 
is no peace, there is no development. He said that the big 
threat to peace in Third World countries is poverty which is the 
main root to cause turmoil in those countries. 
  He appeal to the developing countries, particularly African 
countries to intensify the South-South cooperation and exploit 
their own resources for development. 
  Recalling the previous visits in 1980 and 1988, he said he 
was very much impressed by the Chinese economic development. He 
hoped that the coming visit would further promote friendly 
cooperation between Kenya and China in various domains. 

</TEXT>

