<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Pledges Efforts To Achieve Tax Reform </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Pledges Efforts To Achieve Tax Reform </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2804164094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1628 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804164094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 (XINHUA) -- Japan's new prime 
minister Tsutomu Hata pledged today to strive for Diet 
(Parliament) passage of a tax system reform bill by the year-end 
aimed at increasing the current three percent consumption tax. 
  He told a nationally televised news conference at his 
official residence this evening that the government should 
introduce higher indirect taxes to extend this year's income tax 
cuts into years ahead. 
  Without a hike in indirect taxes, he said, the government 
"cannot finance the income tax cut with the issuance of 
deficit-covering bonds, since the accumulated budget deficit 
will exceed 200 trillion yen (1.9 trillion U.S. dollars). 
  Hata also said his government will abide by any United 
Nations resolutions in seeking a solution to the suspected 
nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula under the constraints of 
Japan's war-renouncing constitution. 
  Asked how his administration would try to overcome 
difficulties of a shaky minority coalition cabinet, Hata said he 
will ask the opposition Liberal Democratic Party and Social 
Democratic Party to cooperate "on whatever policies they can, 
such as the legislation of the budget bills." 
  He dismissed suggestions that he would have no choice but to 
dissolve the 511-seat House of Representatives and call a 
general election in the face of a possible submission of a 
no-confidence motion by the opposition. 

</TEXT>

