<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japan's Business Leaders View New Cabinet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japan's Business Leaders View New Cabinet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2804221494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1642 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804221494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Japan's Business Leaders Show Mixed Reactions to New </F>
Cabinet" -- XINHUA headline] 
  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 (XINHUA) -- Japan's business 
leaders showed mixed reaction to the formation of the minority 
coalition cabinet today of Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata. 
  Some expressed relief at the move that ended 20 days of 
political unrest following Morihiro Hosokawa's April 8 
announcement to resign as prime minister, while others expressed 
concern over political uncertainties stemming from the weak 
foundation of the second coalition cabinet, KYODO NEWS SERVICE 
reported. 
  It quoted Takeshi Nagano, president of the Japan Federation 
of Employers Associations (Nikkeiron), and Osamu Uno, chairman 
of the Japan Department Stores Associations, as commenting on 
the Hata government with different reactions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

