<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian Qichen Receives French Commercial Figure </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Qian Qichen Receives French Commercial Figure </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2804154994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1418 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804154994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 28 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Vice-Premier 
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen met here this afternoon with 
Jean Matteoli, chairman of the Economic and Social Council of 
France. 
  They expressed hopes that bilateral relations will 
experience 
better development. 
  Matteoli and his party arrived here on April 26 on a 
goodwill 
visit to China at the invitation of the National Committee of 
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC). 
  At the meeting, Matteoli said that he is deeply moved by the 
warm reception by the Chinese side after he arrived here, which 
has proved that bilateral relations are on a positive 
development track after the China visit by the French Prime 
Minister Edouard Balladur. 
  He said that French personages from political and economic 
circles spoke highly of the reception of Balladur by China and 
they also hope to further bilateral relations. 
  Matteoli said that his talks with Chinese leaders during the 
past days show that conditions are ready for the harmonious 
development of bilateral relations in the fields of politics, 
economy, culture, science and technology. 
  Qian expressed his appreciation for the active evaluation of 
Sino-French relations, saying that this year is very important 
for their development. 
  He recalled that he was warmly received when he visited 
France in January this year, adding that not long ago, 
Balladur's visit to China was successful. 
  He announced that Gerard Longuet, French minister of 
industry, posts, telecommunications and foreign trade will soon 
visit China, claiming that Sino-French economic and trade 
relations have a new prospect. 
  He pointed out that "we are very pleased to see that the 
development of Sino-French relations has returned to the time 
when the two countries established diplomatic relations." 
  He noted that the tasks facing the leaders of the two 
countries are to carry forward the Sino-French friendly 
relations of cooperation initiated by General Charles de Gaulle, 
former Chairman Mao Zedong and former Premier Zhou Enlai. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

