<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Germany Refutes Alleged Arms Sale to Taiwan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Germany Refutes Alleged Arms Sale to Taiwan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2804092694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0839 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn, April 28 (XINHUA) -- Germany today refuted 
news reports that Bonn will export submarines to Taiwan through 
the United States. 
  The German Government will continue to abide by the decision 
made by the Federal Security Council to ban submarine export to 
Taiwan, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said today on behalf of 
Minister Claus Kinkel. 
  Meanwhile, an Economic Ministry spokesman told reporters 
that 
the German Government had ruled out the possibility of exporting 
submarines to Taiwan via the United States a year before, adding 
that no German shipyards are currently applying for such exports. 
  The denials followed reports in HANDELSBLATT and some other 
German papers that Germany may ship parts of submarines to the 
United States to be assembled there for sale to Taiwan. 
  The reports said the deal is related to Germany's export of 
high- speed trains to Taiwan. 
  On January 28, 1993, the German Federal Security Council had 
rejected requests from business circles for exporting submarines 
and corvettes to Taiwan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

