<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beijing To Launch Industrial Safety Campaign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beijing To Launch Industrial Safety Campaign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2704075194 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST in English 
27 Apr 94 p 10 </F>

<F P=103> HK2704075194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing is to launch a nationwide campaign next 
month to educate workers on the importance of industrial safety. 
  According to official statistics, at least 19 people were 
killed in 17 industrial accidents in the first quarter of this 
year in Beijing. The death toll was, however, significantly 
lower than the 27 recorded during the corresponding period last 
year. Officials said many of this year's victims were 
inexperienced workers under the age of 35. 
  Last year, Shanghai witnessed a 50 percent surge in 
industrial casualties, despite repeated cautions from the 
Government. Labour officials said industrial accidents were 
expected to soar as a result of the increase in the number of 
migrant workers from rural areas arriving in big cities such as 
Beijing and Shanghai. Many of these migrants were farmers who 
had no experience in carrying out industrial work. 
  The lack of safety measures at building sites was a major 
cause of concern. In Shanghai, three workers were buried alive 
while working on an underground drainage project. Government 
officials said that most migrant workers were not aware of their 
legal rights with regard to a safe work environment. Many 
employers failed to comply with safety requirements laid down by 
the Government. 
  The officials said although the Beijing Municipal Government 
had issued regulations four years ago requiring enterprises to 
provide a seven-day course on industrial safety for new workers, 
this was seldom carried out. A study in Shanghai found that 
only two out of 17 township enterprises surveyed had set aside 
special funds -- as the law requires for improving safety 
measures. Some enterprises preferred investing in office 
modernisation to improving safety. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4238 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi083_n_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-083 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   240 Million Tons of Coal Produced in First Quarter </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    240 Million Tons of Coal Produced in First Quarter </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2804122794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1047 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804122794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 28 (XINHUA) -- China produced 240 
million tons of coal in the first three months of this year, up 
6.5 percent over the corresponding period last year. 
  An official from the Ministry of Coal Industry said that in 
the first quarter of this year, state-owned key coal mines 
yielded 110 million tons, whereas local and township mines 
turned out 130 million tons, 12 percent more than in the same 
period last year. 
  He said that in general, the overall coal production of 
state- owned mines remained at the same level as last year; 
however, the developments of these mines varied in different 
regions. 
  The coal output went up in the regions with relatively 
developed industries and advantageous transport, but showed a 
downward trend wherever the railways were clogged, he explained. 
  He said the output of the local and township mines continued 
to grow, but there remained a lot to be done to "rectify, 
transform, unite and upgrade" the township mines. 
  Coal has been the main energy in China, accounting for over 
70 percent of the country's consumption of primary energy 
sources. Fierce competition in the coal markets has been waged 
by producers since the government lifted price controls at the 
beginning of this year. 
  It is expected that the total output of coal will reach 1.16 
billion tons this year. 
  The coal ministry said that it would exercise control over 
the aggregate production, restructure coal products and raise 
the economic efficiency of the industry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

