<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Best-Equipped' Soda Ash Plant Begins Operations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Best-Equipped' Soda Ash Plant Begins Operations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604171594 Beijing XINHUA in English 1501 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604171594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Jinan, April 26 (XINHUA) -- The best-equipped soda 
ash plant in China went into operation today in Weifang, in east 
China's Shandong Province, marking China's step up to the 
advanced world level in the field. 
  It has a planned annual production capacity of 600,000 tons 
of soda ash. 
  The plant, a key construction project of China's Seventh 
Five-Year Plan (1986-1990), involved an investment of 710 
million yuan and is scheduled to produce 400,000 tons of light 
soda ash and 200,000 tons of heavy soda ash annually. 
  Its main equipment has been imported from Germany, Japan and 
the United States. 
  The project, which was started in April 1986 and completed 
in 
June 1989, was built on the largest salt production base in 
China -- Yangkou Salt Farm of Shandong along the Bohai Sea. 
  Since it was put into production on a trial basis, it has 
produced more than 2.4 million tons of 100 percent pure soda 
ash, which has been sold in more than 20 provinces and regions 
in China and exported to 11 countries and regions. 
  In 1993, it produced 640,000 tons of soda ash, 80,000 tons 
of 
which were sold abroad, accounting for one-eighth of the 
nation's total production and more than one-fifth of the 
country's soda ash exports. 
  It has ranked among China's 500 largest industrial 
enterprises for three consecutive years. 

</TEXT>

