<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beijing Speeds Up Construction of Local Railways </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beijing Speeds Up Construction of Local Railways </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604135994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1043 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 26 (XINHUA) -- In the coming ten 
years China will construct more than 70 local railways, with a 
total length of over 7,000 km. 
  Xu Dakun, an official of the Local Railway Association of 
China, said here today that these projects, distributed over 12 
provinces, have already been listed in the Ninth Five-Year Plan 
(1996-2000) of various localities. 
  Xu said that by the end of 1993, China had 81 operating 
local 
railways in 17 provinces and autonomous regions, with a total 
length of over 4,800 km. 
  At present some 20 local railways are being constructed, 
with 
a length of more than 2,000 km. 
  China's local railways experienced a golden development time 
in the past ten years, with over 2,460 km of track laid. The 
total investment during this period was nearly 4.6 billion yuan, 
of which more than 4.1 billion yuan was raised by the local 
governments, while the Ministry of Railways put in 440 million 
yuan. 
  China's local railways are differentiated from state-run 
railways by the characteristics that the construction cost is 
mainly raised by local governments, and the local governments 
have partial or complete management rights. Local railways have 
now become an organic part of China's transport network. 
  To ease the present strained condition of railway transport, 
the Chinese Government has in recent years drafted a series of 
significant policies to promote railway development, which 
include preferential policies encouraging local governments to 
construct railways with self-raised funds. 
  In addition, the Chinese Government also encourages local 
governments to construct railways with overseas funds. So far 
the world bank, the Asian Development Bank, the Japanese 
Government and Taiwan have provided money for local railway 
construction. 
  Xu revealed that six new local railways are prepared to 
introduce overseas construction funds. 
  He said that since the founding of New China in 1949, 
China's 
railways have developed from 22,000 km to more than 54,000 km, 
of which 41 lines, or over 3,100 km, have been constructed by 
local governments and transferred to the state. Some of them 
have now become an important part of the national railway 
network. 
  By the year 2000, China's operating railways will exceed 
8,000 km, with a freight transport volume of 100 million tons, 
Xu added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-4248 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi083_n_94021" </HT>


