<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economists Predict 5 Percent Agricultural Growth </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economists Predict 5 Percent Agricultural Growth </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2704035694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0303 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2704035694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 27 (XINHUA) -- Senior economists 
predicted this week that China's agricultural growth will exceed 
four percent this year, the target set by Premier Li Peng in his 
government work report in spring this year. 
  Economists from the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences and 
the State Statistics Bureau said that if there are no serious 
disasters agriculture will grow by five percent -- and possibly 
by 6.5 percent. 
  They noted that the output of cereals and cotton will see a 
stable growth. For cereals, the rise is expected to be 6.5 
billion kg over last year. 
  Sufficient cereal stockpiles in both state and farmers' 
granaries will maintain a balance between supply and demand, the 
experts said. 
  The per capita income of rural people will increase by three 
percent to four percent, to reach about 1,032 yuan. And the 
total output of rural and township enterprises will grow by 25 
percent to 30 percent. 
  The economists said the expansion of the rural economy is 
backed by a set of government policies and measures to protect 
farmers' interests, increasing investment in agriculture by the 
state, measures to stabilize the planted grain and cotton 
acreages, and special government loans to support key counties 
producing grain and cotton. 

</TEXT>

