<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Surplus Rural Labor Force `Still Large in Numbers' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Surplus Rural Labor Force `Still Large in Numbers' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK2704144494 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 0948 GMT 
27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2704144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 27 (CNS) -- According to an annual 
report on rural economic development (1993-1994) prepared by the 
Rural Development Institute under the Chinese Academy of Social 
Sciences and the Rural Department of the State Statistical 
Bureau, despite the increase in the labour-receiving capacity of 
rural industries including construction, transportation, 
industrial and commercial industries in 1993, the surplus labour 
in rural areas in the country was still large in number. 
  The report shows that the employment structure in rural 
areas 
further improved last year with the scale of township 
enterprises further enlarged and eight million farmers being 
transferred into non-agricultural industries. The newly 
increased working force in the rural areas for the year was, 
however, still put at over seven million resulting in the 
agricultural sector still being overcrowded with 340 million 
labourers involved in it. 
  On how to solve the problem of transferring the surplus 
labour in rural areas to non-agricultural industries, experts in 
this field held that in the coming ten years, China must speed 
up the development of fine-quality and high-efficiency 
agriculture, tertiary industry and the agricultural product 
processing industry as well as the process of urbanization in 
rural areas, realizing the goal of large-scale and consistent 
reduction of surplus labour in rural areas starting from 2010. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

