<F P=100> North Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inner Mongolia Takes Steps To Prevent Export of Fake Products </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Inner Mongolia Takes Steps To Prevent Export of Fake Products </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2904045194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0430 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2904045194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 29 (XINHUA)--The customs authorities 
of North China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region have taken 
steps to strengthen inspection of commodities to prevent exports 
of goods with fake brand names. 
  All personal luggages are strictly examined and inspected, 
and the quantity of luggage a traveller may take is strictly 
limited. No unqualified product is allowed to be taken out of 
the country. 
  Last year the three entry and exit ports of Manzhouli, 
Labudalin and Erlian alone seized fake brand-name products worth 
10 million yuan. 
  The Manzhouli Tourism Bureau provides foreign tourists with 
a 
shopping guide in the Russian language, which reminds tourists 
to demand receipts from Chinese shops. If a commodity can not 
pass customs inspection the buyer can claim compensation from 
the shop. If any travel agent does not provide a tourist with 
the shopping guide and the tourist buys a fake, the travel agent 
is responsible for paying any compensation. 
  These measures are aimed at safeguarding the reputation of 
Chinese-made products and ensuring that cross-border trade 
develops in a healthy way, according to a local official. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

