<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Ruihuan Meets West European Countries' Diplomats </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Ruihuan Meets West European Countries' Diplomats </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604132794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1255 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, April 26 (XINHUA) -- Chairman Li Ruihuan 
of the National Committee of the Chinese People's Political 
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) met here this afternoon with 
diplomatic envoys from five European countries. 
  At the invitation of the governments of Finland, Sweden, 
Norway and Denmark and the Chamber of Representatives and the 
Senate of Belgium, Li will pay official goodwill visits to the 
five countries from May 2 to 21. 
  During the meeting, Li and the diplomats exchanged views on 
the furthering of China's ties with these five countries. 
  Li expressed thanks to these countries for their careful 
arrangements of the visits. 
  "This will be the first trip to Europe by a CPPCC chairman," 
Li told the four ambassadors and one minister-counsellor, saying 
he is looking forward to the visit and the contacts with leaders 
of the five governments and parliaments as well as peoples of 
these countries. 
  The visit is aimed at enhancing mutual understanding, 
expanding exchanges and strengthening cooperation between China 
and the five countries, he noted. 
  China and these countries maintain good ties, which have 
been 
furthered in the past few years. High-level contacts have been 
on the rise and the economic, trade, scientific and 
technological cooperation and cultural exchanges have borne new 
fruit, he said. 
  The two-way trade volume between China and the five 
countries 
has increased by a big margin, he added, voicing the hope that 
potentials be tapped to further expand trade and economic 
cooperation. 
  The five countries have plenty of advanced science and 
technology and management expertise that China should draw from, 
he said. 
  China and the five countries have no conflicts of 
fundamental 
interests and share much common ground on the maintenance of 
peace and promoting common development, he noted. 
  China is ready to further develop its ties with the five 
countries on the principles of seeking common ground while 
reserving differences, mutual respect, non-interference in each 
other's internal affairs and equality and mutual benefit. 
  "The CPPCC is willing to make new efforts for the promotion 
of the existing friendly ties between China and the five 
European countries," he said. 
  Denmark Ambassador to China William Friis-Moller expressed 
his welcome to Li's visit on behalf of the five countries' 
diplomats. 
  The visit has drawn attention from the governments and 
peoples of the five countries, he said. 
  He expressed the hope that the visit will deepen mutual 
understanding, promote the development of bilateral ties and 
provide a chance for the five governments and parliaments to 
know more about China. 

</TEXT>

